@node Handling States Event-by-Event “Event-Leading”
@subsection Handling States Event-by-Event: “Event-Leading”

In this section we start tracking the LED component's on/off state.  This
anticipates extending or refining state behaviour inside the component,
while keeping the component's externally visible behaviour
@emph{exactly} the same as its provided interface or interfaces.

@quotation
@strong{Step 1.} Enter or copy-paste the following new state-management
code in the Dezyne editor.  You can continue with the system design from
the previous section, or restart with only the below code.

@example
@kwd{import ILED.dzn;}

@kwd{component} LED @{
  @kwd{provides} ILED iLed;

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    @kwd{enum} State @{ Off, On @};
    State state = State.Off;
    @kwd{on} iLed.turnOn(): @{ state = State.On; @}
    @kwd{on} iLed.turnOff(): @{ state = State.Off; @}
  @}
@}
@end example
@end quotation
In the above component's code, the @kwd{enum} line declares an
enumeration type as in C/C++/Java.  “Off” and “On” are unique @emph{enum
values} for this particular enumeration type, @emph{not} strings.
“State” is a case-sensitive user-defined name for the enumeration type.

The next line after the @kwd{enum} declaration defines a variable
named “state” of type State and initializes the setting to “Off”.  By
convention in this tutorial we will always list the default state first
when declaring an enum.  Two important but non-obvious points:

@itemize
@item
You are @emph{required} to initialize an enumeration-type variable in
its declaration.

@item
You @emph{cannot} split this declaration-assignment line into the two
lines, e.g.“State state; state = State.Off” -- this equals sign is a
special initialization operator, not a generic assignment (try it).

@end itemize

Each handler line (@kwd{on event}) in the component's behaviour block
is followed either by one statement that ends in a semicolon, or by
curly braces @{@} that contain zero (no-op) or one or more statements.

@quotation
@strong{Step 2.} View the component's State Chart, shown below (you
might have to refresh/update views first using the
@image{images/update_icon.75,,,,.png}
 icon in Dezyne-IDE, next to the verify
@image{images/verify_icon.75,,,,.png}
icon)
@end quotation

@image{images/state_2,,,,.png}

@node Interface States versus Component States
@subsection Interface States versus Component States

You can track states in an interface exactly as you can in a component.
When defined in an interface, state declarations differ from the
component's only by 1) having no interface-instance prefix, and 2)
having no parentheses.  Here are the same states as above, but defined
instead in the interface:

@example
@kwd{interface} ILED @{
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} turnOn();
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} turnOff();

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    @kwd{enum} State @{ Off, On @};
    State state = State.Off;
    @kwd{on} turnOn: @{ state = State.On; @}
    @kwd{on} turnOff: @{ state = State.Off; @}
  @}
@}
@end example

It is important to understand that there are at least two occasions when
one might choose to declare and manage state-related enumerations in an
interface:

@itemize
@item
When the providing component or components are hand-written, i.e., have
no behaviour blocks and therefore no declared state behaviour, yet
enumerated state behaviour is of interest to requiring (calling)
components.

@item
When an interface function will synchronously return enumerated results
that inform the caller of a new state arrived at (at least momentarily)
as a consequence of the function call.

@end itemize

If you define states in both an interface and in a providing component
for that interface, Dezyne verification will ignore the interface's
declared states and only compare the component's function return values
with the interface's specified function return values.

@emph{There is no direct connection between states defined in an
interface's behavioural specification and states defined in a providing
component's implemented} @emph{behaviour.  All that matters is that every
stimulus applied to a component-implemented interface function returns a
response type that matches the interface's declared response type, i.e.
that every trace through the interface matches every trace through the
implementing component for events related to just this interface.} For
example, we will see later that a model function can be defined to
return an integer within a fixed range; verification will find
@emph{any} case of a return outside this range, and will display, in the
Trace View window, the exact sequence of steps that led to the mismatch.

@quotation
@quotation
@center @strong{Debugging a Model: Interface specification versus Implementation}

Dezyne verification examines all possible sequences of execution through
a provided interface.  Verification finds each mismatch between
implementation and specification -- e.g., return types, missing events,
output events, etc -- and displays the entire trace of events that led
to the mismatch.  Thus, you can quickly and inexpensively fix buried
logical errors like race conditions and deadlocks @emph{even before any
source code is generated or written}.
@end quotation
@end quotation

@node Handling Events State-by-State “State-Leading”
@subsection Handling Events State-by-State: “State-Leading”

The component behaviour as written so far handles state changes
event-by-event.  It unconditionally turns the light off when directed,
whether the light was on or not, and turns it on when directed.

You can invert behavioural logic to handle events state-by-state.  The
Dezyne language supports if-then-else but not at the first logical level
within a state's behaviour block -- we'll see this in a later section.

Top-level logic inside a @kwd{behaviour} block can only be one of
these three different kinds:

@itemize
@item
Declaration plus initialization of an enum or a variable.

@item
An on-event block.

@item
A [boolean-test] “guard” block as used below.

@end itemize

@quotation
@strong{Step 1.} Enter or copy-paste the below code into your ILED-LED
design and verify it.

@example
@kwd{import ILED.dzn;}

@kwd{component} LED @{
  @kwd{provides} ILED iLed;

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    @kwd{enum} State @{ Off, On @};
    State state = State.Off;
    [state == State.Off] @{
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOn(): @{ state = State.On; @}
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOff(): @{@}
    @}
    [state == State.On] @{
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOn(): @{@}
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOff(): @{ state = State.Off; @}
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example
@end quotation
Important rule: The Dezyne verification “compliance” check tests that a
component's behaviour with respect to a given interface handles all
possible events associated with that interface.  If you handle events
purely state-by-state as in the above example, then for
@kwd{component} compliance and for zero ambiguity @emph{you must
explicitly handle every on-event inside each state-oriented guard block}
(there is one exception to this rule involving “illegal” situations,
which is explained later.).

@quotation
@strong{Step 2.} Comment out line “@kwd{on iLed.turnOff(): @{@}}” in
the above code and re-verify.  You will get a compliance error even
though you've seemingly changed nothing in the component's visible
behaviour.  This error can be reported fully only via the Trace and
Sequence Views:
@end quotation

@image{images/verification_error_1.75,,,,.png}

The user interface's Console output for the above verification is shown
below; the series of events that arrived at the compliance error precede
the Exit Code line.

@example
dzn$ @b{dzn --session=22 -v verify --model=LED Intro\LED-State-Leading.dzn}
..
verify: ILED: check: completeness: ok
verify: ILED: check: deadlock: ok
verify: ILED: check: livelock: ok
verify: LED: check: deterministic: ok
verify: LED: check: illegal: ok
verify: LED: check: deadlock: ok
verify: LED: check: livelock: ok
Intro/LED-State-Leading.dzn:14:5:i19: iLed.turnOn not handled
verify: LED: check: compliance: fail
iLed.turnOn
iLed.return
iLed.turnOn
@b{Exit Code: 1}
dzn$
@end example

The Dezyne “@code{==}” comparison operator works as in
C/C++/C#/Java.  Each @code{[]} guard must be followed by either a single
statement or a curly-bracket block @code{@{@}} with or without
statements in it; you can always remove curly brackets where they
contain exactly one statement.  You can optionally further abbreviate the
guard equality test for states whenever there would be no ambiguity, as
shown below.  We will abbreviate these ways from here on wherever
possible.

@quotation
@strong{Step 3.} Modify and verify your design using shorthand guard
statements and event handler logic as shown below.

@example
@kwd{import ILED.dzn;}

@kwd{component} LED @{
  @kwd{provides} ILED iLed;

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    @kwd{enum} State @{ Off, On @};
    State state = State.Off;
    [state.Off] @{
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOn(): state = State.On;
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOff(): @{@}
    @}
    [state.On] @{
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOn(): @{@}
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOff(): state = State.Off;
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example
@end quotation
From this point on we will leave out the Step-by-Step cues and instead
sometimes suggest Exercises to try out on your own before copy-pasting
code into the editor.  No matter how you proceed, you must always run
verification on your edits!

@node Polling for State
@subsection Polling for State

Sometimes a component that sets another component's state needs to poll
(query) for the current state.  The below shows how to enable polling
through a “getter” function.

In order to support and verify the getState reply below, we have to
declare the state enumeration publicly in the interface definition,
@emph{reference} the interface enumeration in the component (not declare
it), and replicate at least some of the component's state behaviour in
the interface behaviour.

The interface code below uses the event-first pattern to define its
internal behaviour.  The rule is, as before, that all states or guards
must be handled by the defined behaviour.  The getState handler below
does the same thing in every state, thus it does not use @code{[]}
boolean checks.

Exercise: simplify the below interface's code so that none of the
on-event handlers tests the state, instead each on-event handler does
the same thing in all states.  Answers are at the end of this section.

@example
@kwd{interface} ILED @{
  @kwd{enum} State @{ Off, On @};
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} turnOn();
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} turnOff();
  @kwd{in} State getState();

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    State state = State.Off;
    @kwd{on} turnOn: @{
      [state.Off] state = State.On;
      [state.On] @{@}
    @}
    @kwd{on} turnOff: @{
      [state.Off] @{@}
      [state.On] state = State.Off;
    @}
    @kwd{on} getState: @{ @kwd{reply}(state); @}
  @}
@}

@kwd{component} LED @{
  @kwd{provides} ILED iLed;

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    ILED.State state = ILED.State.Off;
    [state.Off] @{
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOn(): state = ILED.State.On;
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOff(): @{@}
      @kwd{on} iLed.getState(): @kwd{reply}(state);
    @}
    [state.On] @{
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOn(): @{@}
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOff(): state = ILED.State.Off;
      @kwd{on} iLed.getState(): @kwd{reply}(state);
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example

As noted earlier and shown here again, for state-leading-only logic,
every input event (“in” function) must be handled either explicitly or
implicitly inside every @code{[state]} block, else your model will have
unhandled-event verification errors (compliance).

Exercise answers -- the first one mixes event-leading and state-leading
logic:

@example
@kwd{component} LED @{
  @kwd{provides} ILED iLed;

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    ILED.State state = ILED.State.Off;
    // mix event-leading and state-leading
    @kwd{on} iLed.getState(): @kwd{reply}(state);
    [state.Off] @{
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOn(): state = ILED.State.On;
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOff(): @{@}
    @}
    [state.On] @{
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOn(): @{@}
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOff(): state = ILED.State.Off;
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example

Exercise second answer, with minimal logic:

@example
@kwd{component} LED @{
  @kwd{provides} ILED iLed;

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    ILED.State state = ILED.State.Off;
    // minimal model of equivalent logic
    @kwd{on} iLed.turnOn(): state = ILED.State.On;
    @kwd{on} iLed.turnOff(): state = ILED.State.Off;
    @kwd{on} iLed.getState(): @kwd{reply}(state);
  @}
@}
@end example

@node States and Illegal Events Asserts
@subsection States and Illegal Events: Asserts

Suppose that the LED component insists that callers track its state and
never call function turnOn() when the light is already on.  Our simple
example wouldn't suffer from such a call, but a wrong call in a
life-critical medical device could be devastating.  Dezyne's
@kwd{illegal} keyword expresses the concept of, “if execution reaches
this line then there is a crucial defect somewhere in your logic”.  An
interface and its providing component must express exactly the same
legal and illegal behaviour @emph{as seen by a caller}.  Dezyne-generated
source code resolves each @kwd{illegal} as an assert() statement or
equivalent.

@example
@kwd{interface} ILED @{
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} turnOn();
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} turnOff();

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    @kwd{enum} State @{ Off, On @};
    State state = State.Off;
    @kwd{on} turnOn: @{
      [state.Off] state = State.On;
      [state.On] @kwd{illegal};
    @}
    @kwd{on} turnOff: @{
      [state.On] state = State.Off;
      [state.Off] @kwd{illegal};
    @}
  @}
@}

@kwd{component} LED @{
  @kwd{provides} ILED iLed;

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    @kwd{enum} State @{ Off, On @};
    State state = State.Off;
    [state.Off] @{
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOn(): state = State.On;
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOff(): @kwd{illegal};
    @}
    [state.On] @{
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOn(): @kwd{illegal};
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOff(): state = State.Off;
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example

In your model code, mismatches between an interface and its provider
that involve @kwd{illegal} will show up as verification errors, but
only the Trace and Sequence views can point out the exact problem.  Once
any such mismatches are resolved, simulation in the Dezyne-IDE editor will
not allow an illegal call to be initiated as an event -- such a call
will not be “eligible” in Dezyne's terminology.

As mentioned earlier, when using state-leading logic, there is one
exception to the rule that each event must be declared and handled
explicitly in each state in a providing component's behaviour
implementation.  If a particular event is illegal in a particular state,
you are allowed to omit that declaration in the @emph{component's}
behaviour; Dezyne will assume that this is an @kwd{illegal} and
will check the interface specification for confirmation.  The generated
code will have an assert in the same spot where the explicit declaration
would have placed it.  To see this exception in action, comment out one
of the component's illegals as shown below and re-verify:

@example
@kwd{component} LED @{
  @kwd{provides} ILED iLed;

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    @kwd{enum} State @{ Off, On @};
    State state = State.Off;
    [state.Off] @{
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOn(): state = State.On;
      // @kwd{on} iLed.turnOff(): @kwd{illegal};
    @}
    [state.On] @{
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOn(): @kwd{illegal};
      @kwd{on} iLed.turnOff(): state = State.Off;
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example

Uncluttering code by making use of implicit illegals has the downside of
hiding logic from a code reviewer.

@node Time and Timers Making an LED Blink
@section Time and Timers: Making an LED Blink

Language keywords: @kwd{bool} @kwd{extern} @kwd{false}
@kwd{inevitable} @kwd{out} @kwd{true}

Operator: @kwd{!}

Dezyne's logical models have no inherent concept of time; instead,
Dezyne only knows sequences of events and responses to events.  Model
verification proceeds by examining, directly or indirectly, every
possible eligible-event-initiated trace path through the component
and/or interface(s) being verified.  Each step in an underway
verification trace represents zero elapsed time in the modeled system
(and takes very little computation time during verification).  Any
verification trace stops immediately upon finding an error, thus running
to completion signals that no logic-related errors were found in the
model.

Dezyne can model and verify repeating behaviour.  We'll build a timer
interface that makes our LED blink on and off at constant time
intervals, and that works as-is in auto-generated C++ source code.  The
entirely new -- but nearly all familiar -- code below defines a simple
timer interface and a hand-written component that will implement the
interface.  An @kwd{out} function names an event that a requiring
(calling) component has to handle in its behaviour.

@example
@kwd{interface} ITimer @{
  @kwd{enum} State @{ Idle, Running @};
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} start();
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} cancel();
  @kwd{out} @kwd{void} timeout();

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    State state = State.Idle;
    [state.Idle] @{
      @kwd{on} start: state = State.Running;
      @kwd{on} cancel: @{@}
    @}
    [state.Running] @{
      @kwd{on} start: @kwd{illegal};
      @kwd{on} cancel: state = State.Idle;
      @kwd{on} @kwd{inevitable}: @{ // ALWAYS happens eventually unless cancelled first
        state = State.Idle;
        timeout;
      @}
    @}
  @}
@}

@kwd{component} Timer @{
  @kwd{provides} ITimer iTimer;
@}
@end example

Dezyne @kwd{inevitable} keyword indicates that the timeout event
will @emph{always} eventually happen during model verification, to test
all possible execution paths, including the possibility of a timeout
@emph{just} before a cancel call arrives.  The @kwd{inevitable}
keyword has a companion we'll discuss later, @kwd{optional}, which
means “usually happens but might never happen”; both these keywords are
used @emph{only} in interfaces, to inform verification about certain
special conditions it must check.

Note in the above the asymmetry between the Idle state and the Running
state.  The interface says it's OK to cancel when the timer is idle, but
it's illegal to try to start when the timer is running.  We assume the
caller will manage its own state with respect to use of the timer.

The next version of the timer shows how to pass a parameter of a
particular type to a model method.

@example
@kwd{interface} ITimer @{
  @kwd{extern} long_integer $long$; // source code data type will be long
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} start(long_integer milliseconds);
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} cancel();
  @kwd{out} @kwd{void} timeout();

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    @kwd{enum} State @{ Idle, Running @};
    State state = State.Idle;
    [state.Idle] @{
      @kwd{on} start: state = State.Running;
      @kwd{on} cancel: @{@}
    @}
    [state.Running] @{
      @kwd{on} start: @kwd{illegal};
      @kwd{on} cancel: state = State.Idle;
      @kwd{on} @kwd{inevitable}: @{ // ALWAYS happens eventually unless cancelled first
        state = State.Idle;
        timeout;
      @}
    @}
  @}
@}

@kwd{component} Timer @{
  @kwd{provides} ITimer iTimer;
@}
@end example

The @kwd{extern} keyword above maps a model data type to an indicated
data type in Dezyne-generated source, via string substitution.  For
example, the above sample leads to this line in generated C++ code:

@example
@b{std::function<void (long milliseconds)> start;}
@end example

Now we integrate the timer into the LED controller.  The interface
definition below is complete; it uses the events-leading pattern.

@example
@kwd{interface} ILED @{
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} shine();
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} darken();
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} blink();

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    @kwd{enum} State @{ Dark, Shining, Blinking @};
    State state = State.Dark;
    @kwd{on} shine: @{ state = State.Shining; @}
    @kwd{on} blink: @{ state = State.Blinking; @}
    @kwd{on} darken: @{ state = State.Dark; @}
  @}
@}
@end example

This interface allows a caller to reset the LED to the same state it's
already in.  Below is a partial implementation of the blinkable LED
component, sketching in a states-leading approach.  You can create this
exact component in Dezyne (though it might need a different name) and
verify that it conforms to both the ILED interface and the ITimer
interface, even though the interface expresses its logic in
event-leading format.  Also, in this component we will track the LED's
lit/dark state as part of managing the blinking state; as with state
variables we have to initialize any boolean variable in its declaration.

@example
@kwd{component} LED @{
  @kwd{provides} ILED iLed;
  @kwd{requires} ITimer iTimer;

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    @kwd{enum} State @{ Dark, Shining, Blinking @};
    State state = State.Dark;
    @kwd{bool} lit = @kwd{false};
    [state.Dark] @{
      @kwd{on} iLed.shine(): @{@}
      @kwd{on} iLed.darken(): @{@}
      @kwd{on} iLed.blink(): @{@}
      @kwd{on} iTimer.timeout(): @{@}
    @}
    [state.Shining] @{
      @kwd{on} iLed.shine(): @{@}
      @kwd{on} iLed.darken(): @{@}
      @kwd{on} iLed.blink(): @{@}
      @kwd{on} iTimer.timeout(): @{@}
    @}
    [state.Blinking] @{
      @kwd{on} iLed.shine(): @{@}
      @kwd{on} iLed.darken(): @{@}
      @kwd{on} iLed.blink(): @{@}
      @kwd{on} iTimer.timeout(): @{@}
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example

In the above, we have added a new @kwd{bool} variable named “lit” to
track the shining-darkened state changes when the LED is blinking.  The
light is off by default, hence variable lit is initialized to
@kwd{false}.  Booleans work in Dezyne as they do in C/C++/Java,
including the negation operator !.

Filling in the event handlers for the initially dark LED:

@example
  [state.Dark] @{
    @kwd{on} iLed.shine(): @{ // -> Shining, lit
      state = State.Shining;
      lit = @kwd{true};
    @}
    @kwd{on} iLed.darken(): @{@} // ignore
    @kwd{on} iLed.blink(): @{ // -> Blinking, half-second timer
      lit = @kwd{false};
      state = State.Blinking;
      iTimer.start($500$);
    @}
    @kwd{on} iTimer.timeout(): @{@} // shouldn't occur, just ignore
  @}
@end example

The Shining state event handlers are essentially the same as for Dark.
Blinking state handlers are below.  When Blinking, on each timer timeout
the light switches between off and on and restarts the timer.

@example
  [state.Blinking] @{
    @kwd{on} iLed.shine(): @{
      iTimer.cancel();
      state = State.Shining;
    @}
    @kwd{on} iLed.darken(): @{
      iTimer.cancel();
      state = State.Dark;
    @}
    @kwd{on} iLed.blink(): @{@}
    @kwd{on} iTimer.timeout(): @{
      lit = !lit;
      iTimer.start($500$);
    @}
  @}
@end example

You can use @kwd{if} @kwd{else} instead of the negation operator
when handling the timeout, as below.  In Dezyne, the if-else construct
can appear only within on-event behaviour.

@example
  [state.Blinking] @{
    @kwd{on} iLed.shine(): @{
      iTimer.cancel();
      state = State.Shining;
    @}
    @kwd{on} iLed.darken(): @{
      iTimer.cancel();
      state = State.Dark;
    @}
    @kwd{on} iLed.blink(): @{@}
    @kwd{on} iTimer.timeout(): @{
      @kwd{if} (lit) @{ lit = @kwd{false}; @} @kwd{else} @{ lit = @kwd{true}; @}
      iTimer.start($500$);
    @}
  @}
@end example

As an exercise you should complete the [state.Shining] event handlers,
then verify and simulate.

