@node Requirements
@subsection Requirements

Our next alarm system has a pincode keypad, a multi-color LED, a siren,
and sensors.  The keypad silently discards invalid pincodes.  The system
has two basic sequences of events:

@quotation
On power up the system is unarmed, the LED is green, and sensors are
disabled.
@enumerate
@item
Green: unarmed.
@item
Yellow: Valid pincode entry arms the system, turns the LED yellow and
enables sensors.
@item
Red: A sensor trigger disables the sensors and turns the LED red.
@item
Either Yellow: Valid pincode entry soon enough cancels the timer and
returns the system to the armed state with yellow LED and enabled
sensors.
@item
Or Red with siren: Timer timeout turns on the siren.
@item
Yellow: Valid pincode entry turns off the siren and returns to armed
state.
@end enumerate
@end quotation

@quotation
Alternate sequence with no sensor trigger event:
@enumerate
@item
Green: Unarmed
@item
Yellow: Valid pincode entry arms the system, turns the LED yellow, and
enables sensors.
@item
Green: Valid pincode entry disarms the system, turns the LED green, and
disables sensors.
@end enumerate
@end quotation

One might white-board the initial conceptual system like this:

@image{images/state_3,,,,.jpg}

After power-up, a valid pincode event can arrive any time at the
Controller, whether appropriate or not.  Once the Controller enables the
sensors, they can trigger events at any moment but possibly never.  The
LED is configured to be a solid-color green on power-up, yellow when
armed, and red whenever there is a sensor-generated alarm active.  The
Controller starts the timer when a sensor triggers and starts the siren
upon timeout.  A user must enter a valid pincode to exit the alarm state
and to silence the siren if it has begun sounding.

@node The Controller
@subsection The Controller

Usually we start designing by sketching interfaces, since we can always
reasonably assume that a “hand-written” component will correctly
implement any given interface.  The below interface captures the two main
kinds of incoming events for the controller: user-entered pincodes, and
sensor trigger events.  Timer timeout events are different since the
controller has to initiate them.

@example
@kwd{interface} IController @{
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} validPincode();
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} sensorTriggered();

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    @kwd{on} validPincode: @{@}
    @kwd{on} sensorTriggered: @{@}
  @}
@}
@end example

The above minimal interface declares implicitly that any and every
incoming event is “legal”, i.e., the caller does not have to track the
controller's state and avoid inappropriate calls.  Said another way, the
implemented interface will not hit an assertion via an @kwd{illegal}
event.

A minimal Controller component would start up Unarmed; go from there to
Armed upon a valid pincode; go from Armed to Alarming upon getting a
sensorTriggered event; return to Armed state upon valid pincode; and
return to Unarmed after another valid pincode.  As an exercise you might
want to build the minimal controller yourself before reading the below
code.

@example
@kwd{component} Controller @{
  @kwd{provides} IController iController;

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    @kwd{enum} State @{ Unarmed, Armed, Alarming @};
    State state = State.Unarmed;
    [state.Unarmed] @{
      @kwd{on} iController.validPincode(): state = State.Armed;
      @kwd{on} iController.sensorTriggered(): @{@}
    @}
    [state.Armed] @{
      @kwd{on} iController.validPincode(): state = State.Unarmed;
      @kwd{on} iController.sensorTriggered():state = State.Alarming;
    @}
    [state.Alarming] @{
      @kwd{on} iController.validPincode(): state = State.Armed;
      @kwd{on} iController.sensorTriggered(): @{@}
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example

The above honors its interface contract by always silently accepting and
ignoring a sensorTriggered event when it is not in the Armed state.

@node Adding the LED
@subsection Adding the LED

Next we add simple control for an LED.

@example
@kwd{interface} ILED @{
  // assumes green automatically on power-up
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} setGreen();
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} setYellow();
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} setRed();
  @kwd{behaviour} @{ @kwd{on} setGreen, setYellow, setRed: @{@} @}
@}

@kwd{component} LED @{ @kwd{provides} ILED iLed; @}
@end example

Integrating the LED would make a good exercise.

Note that the below integrated code @emph{imports} the LED interface as
opposed to declaring it.

@example
@kwd{import} LED.dzn;

@kwd{interface} IController @{
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} validPincode();
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} sensorTriggered();

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    @kwd{on} validPincode: @{@}
    @kwd{on} sensorTriggered: @{@}
  @}
@}

@kwd{component} Controller @{
  @kwd{provides} IController iController;
  @kwd{requires} ILED iLed;

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    @kwd{enum} State @{ Unarmed, Armed, Alarming @};
    State state = State.Unarmed;
    [state.Unarmed] @{
      @kwd{on} iController.validPincode(): @{
        state = State.Armed;
        iLed.setYellow();
      @}
      @kwd{on} iController.sensorTriggered(): @{@}
    @}
    [state.Armed] @{
      @kwd{on} iController.validPincode(): @{
        state = State.Unarmed;
        iLed.setGreen();
      @}
      @kwd{on} iController.sensorTriggered(): @{
        state = State.Alarming;
        iLed.setRed();
      @}
    @}
    [state.Alarming] @{
      @kwd{on} iController.validPincode(): @{
        state = State.Armed;
        iLed.setYellow();
      @}
      @kwd{on} iController.sensorTriggered(): @{@}
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example

@node Adding the Sensors
@subsection Adding the Sensors

Now we add sensors, removing the sensorTriggered event from the
Controller and importing the sensor we constructed earlier.

@example
@kwd{import} LED.dzn;
@kwd{import} Sensor.dzn;

@kwd{interface} IController @{
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} validPincode();
  @kwd{behaviour} @{ @kwd{on} validPincode: @{@} @}
@}

@kwd{component} Controller @{
  @kwd{provides} IController iController;
  @kwd{requires} ILED iLed;
  @kwd{requires} ISensor iSensor;

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    @kwd{enum} State @{ Unarmed, Armed, Alarming @};
    State state = State.Unarmed;
    [state.Unarmed] @{
      @kwd{on} iController.validPincode(): @{
        iSensor.turnOn();
        state = State.Armed;
        iLed.setYellow();
      @}
      @kwd{on} iSensor.triggered(): @{@}
    @}
    [state.Armed] @{
      @kwd{on} iController.validPincode(): @{
        iSensor.turnOff();
        state = State.Unarmed;
        iLed.setGreen();
      @}
      @kwd{on} iSensor.triggered(): @{
        iSensor.turnOff();
        state = State.Alarming;
        iLed.setRed();
      @}
    @}
    [state.Alarming] @{
      @kwd{on} iController.validPincode(): @{
        iSensor.turnOn();
        state = State.Armed;
        iLed.setYellow();
      @}
      @kwd{on} iSensor.triggered(): @kwd{illegal};
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example

@node Adding the Siren and Timer
@subsection Adding the Siren and Timer

Next we add a siren to be sounded only when a user takes too long to
enter the pincode after a sensor trigger makes the LED go red.  The siren
interface and component are simple:

@example
@kwd{interface} ISiren @{
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} turnOn();
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} turnOff();
  @kwd{behaviour} @{ @kwd{on} turnOn, turnOff: @{@}
  @}
@}

@kwd{component} Siren @{ @kwd{provides} ISiren iSiren; @}
@end example

We'll put the siren in its own file Siren.dzn and include that file in
the Controller.  In the next step we turn on the siren whenever Alarming,
and turn it off whenever returning to the Armed state.

@example
@kwd{import} LED.dzn;
@kwd{import} Sensor.dzn;
@kwd{import} Siren.dzn;

@kwd{interface} IController @{
  @kwd{in} @kwd{void} validPincode();
  @kwd{behaviour} @{ @kwd{on} validPincode: @{@} @}
@}

@kwd{component} Controller @{
  @kwd{provides} IController iController;
  @kwd{requires} ILED iLed;
  @kwd{requires} ISensor iSensor;
  @kwd{requires} ISiren iSiren;

  @kwd{behaviour} @{
    @kwd{enum} State @{ Unarmed, Armed, Alarming @};
    State state = State.Unarmed;
    [state.Unarmed] @{
      @kwd{on} iController.validPincode(): @{
        iSensor.turnOn();
        state = State.Armed;
        iLed.setYellow();
      @}
      @kwd{on} iSensor.triggered(): @{@}
    @}
    [state.Armed] @{
      @kwd{on} iController.validPincode(): @{
        iSensor.turnOff();
        state = State.Unarmed;
        iLed.setGreen();
      @}
      @kwd{on} iSensor.triggered(): @{
        iSensor.turnOff();
        state = State.Alarming;
        iLed.setRed();
        iSiren.turnOn();
      @}
    @}
    [state.Alarming] @{
      @kwd{on} iController.validPincode(): @{
        iSensor.turnOn();
        state = State.Armed;
        iLed.setYellow();
        iSiren.turnOff();
      @}
      @kwd{on} iSensor.triggered(): @kwd{illegal};
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example

As an exercise, modify the above model to turn on the siren only on a
30-second timeout after the system has been triggered into the Alarming
state.  You will need to import the Timer component we created earlier
and configure it correctly.  The fragment of model code below shows only
the key changes needed to the Controller event handling; if you copy and
paste this partial solution into Dezyne you will still have to debug and
finish it.

@example
      @kwd{on} iSensor.triggered(): @{
        iSensor.turnOff();
        state = State.Alarming;
        iLed.setRed();
        iTimer.start($30000$);
      @}
      @kwd{on} iTimer.timeout(): @kwd{illegal};
    @}
    [state.Alarming] @{
      @kwd{on} iTimer.timeout(): @{
        iSiren.turnOn();
      @}
      @kwd{on} iController.validPincode(): @{
        iTimer.cancel();
        iSensor.turnOn();
        state = State.Armed;
        iLed.setYellow();
        iSiren.turnOff();
      @}
@end example

@node The Completed Alarm System
@subsection The Completed Alarm System

Below is the Dezyne-generated sequence diagram, and event trace listing,
from simulating a complete round-trip exercise of the Controller
component.  Events included sounding the siren when the user did not
enter a valid pincode soon enough after an alarm was triggered, and
returning at the end to the disarmed state.  (Screen shots were edited
for better readability.)

@image{images/sequence_1,,,,.png}

We finish the alarm system by creating a top-level system component that
shows how the other components interconnect through interfaces.  This
system component presents the iController interface to the yet larger
software system into which it might be integrated.  For this tutorial,
the system component's purpose is only to auto-generate the diagram
shown below the code.

@example
@kwd{component} AlarmSystem @{
  @kwd{provides} IController iController;

  @kwd{system} @{
    Controller controller;
    LED led;
    Sensor sensor;
    Siren siren;
    Timer timer;
    iController<=>controller.iController;
    controller.iLed<=>led.iLed;
    controller.iSensor<=>sensor.iSensor;
    controller.iSiren<=>siren.iSiren;
    controller.iTimer<=>timer.iTimer;
  @}
@}
@end example

@image{images/system_3,,,,.png}

@quotation
@quotation
@center @strong{Refactoring and Extending Dezyne Models}

Dezyne models capture fundamental logical behaviour in perhaps a quarter
of the lines it takes to write the same logic in compatible and usable
C++.  The five Dezyne models in the alarm system all have tens of lines
of code each.  Because Dezyne model representations are compact, easily
edited and complete/compliant, they make refactoring ant extending as
easy as it could possible be.  Further, because Dezyne quickly verifies
any change or addition to an existing model, the pace of refactoring and
extending is as fast as it could possibly be.
@end quotation
@end quotation

@quotation
@quotation
@center @strong{Comparing Using Dezyne to Developing ``By Hand''}

Think about having to develop this system ``in the other
direction''.  You'd likely start with sketched sequence diagrams, which
are tedious and difficult to draw manually and modify.  From there you
would specify and write the C++ source code, and build and test
is.  Along the way you would almost certainly rebuild the sequence
diagram by hand more than once.

Eventually a test/verification persom would have to manually generate
event sequences to exercise paths through the system.  That person could
take weeks or months to do what Dezyne did in a few seconds: trace out
every possible execution path through the system and ensure there are no
race conditions, deadlocks, non-deterministic overlaps among guards, or
other problems.

In fact, @emph{for anything but the smallest system, your
test/verification staff will probably NEVER accomplish what Dezyne has
done in seconds or minutes, which is attain 100% path coverage for the
heart of the system, its core states-and communications logic}.  @b{This
is the power of Dezyne}
@end quotation
@end quotation

@c *********************************************************************
@node Dezyne Code Integration
@chapter Dezyne Code Integration

In this chapter we will

@itemize
@item
Integrate every kind of event type in Dezyne with handwritten (hereafter
foreign) code

@item
Navigate through the essential areas of generated code

@item
Create a environment for the generated code to run in

@item
Look into the Dezyne runtime is and how it should be used within
your own application

@item
Compile an application consisting of foreign and generated code (in C++)
@end itemize

We assume that you are familiar with the basics of the Dezyne modeling
language and have some affinity with C++, GNU/Linux and the Raspberry Pi.  It
is assumed you are somewhat familiar with software designed from an
event-based approach
(@url{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Event-driven_programming}).

The examples shown throughout this chapter will be using the Dezyne-IDE,
although Dezyne can also be used as a stand-alone command line
client.  It is assumed that you have a Dezyne-IDE running on
your system before starting this tutorial.

Furthermore, in this chapter you we will use lambda expressions and
polymorphism/inheritance in C++.  If you are unfamiliar with these
concepts, you may find the following resources useful:

@itemize
@item
Lambda expressions:
@uref{http://www.cprogramming.com/c++11/c++11-lambda-closures.html,http://www.cprogramming.com/c++11/c++11-lambda-closures.html}

@item
Polymorphism/inheritance:
@uref{http://www.cplusplus.com/doc/tutorial/polymorphism/,http://www.cplusplus.com/doc/tutorial/polymorphism/}

@end itemize

