Take note that we will be showing the integration steps only; we will
not focus on the functional implementation.

@menu
* Integrating code in C#::
* Foreign components in C#::
@end menu

@node Integrating code in C#
@subsection Integrating code in C#

Creating instances of the required runtime libraries is done similar to
how it is done in C++.  In C#, it is easier in the sense that no
additional files must be included on a per-file basis.  Preparing the
runtime libraries is done as follows:

@example
using System;

namespace MyDznApp @{
  class main @{
    private dzn.Locator dznLoc;
    private dzn.Runtime dznRt;

    public static void Main() @{
      dznLoc = new dzn.Locator();
      dznRt = new dzn.Runtime();

      dznLoc.set(dznRt);
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example

Take note that @code{Locator} and @code{Runtime} are located in the dzn
namespace.  Depending on the execution semantics of your application,
you may choose to define the objects within the scope of @code{Main} or
outside the scope (as can be seen above).

Creating an object to represent the System generated from Dezyne models
requires you to pass the dzn.Locator object you created as parameter:

@example
using System;

namespace MyDznApp @{
  class main @{
    private dzn.Locator dznLoc;
    private dzn.Runtime dznRt;
    private AlarmSystem as;

    public static void Main() @{
      dznLoc = new dzn.Locator();
      dznRt = new dzn.Runtime();

      dznLoc.set(dznRt);
      as = new AlarmSystem(dznLoc);
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example

In C#, events are generated as @code{Action} or @code{Func} objects, the
C# variant of function objects.  @code{Action} is used for void on
events; @code{Func} is used for on events that have a return value.  To
reach an event on a port of a component, the following structure is
applied in generated C#:

@code{ComponentName.PortName.PortDirection.EventName}, where
@var{ComponentName} is the name of the data object representing the
Component, @var{PortName} is the name of the Port you are trying to
access, @var{PortDirection} is either inport or outport depending on the
specification and @var{EventName} is the name of the on event you are
trying to access.

As an example, let's invoke the validPincode event on the provided
iController port of the AlarmSystem (required action for
@emph{Provides/in} and @emph{Requires/out}):

@example
using System;

namespace MyDznApp @{
  class main @{
    private dzn.Locator dznLoc;
    private dzn.Runtime dznRt;
    private AlarmSystem as;

    public static void Main() @{
      dznLoc = new dzn.Locator();
      dznRt = new dzn.Runtime();

      dznLoc.set(dznRt);
      as = new AlarmSystem(as);

      as.iController.inport.validPincode();
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example

Here, the ComponentName is @code{as}; PortName is @code{iController};
PortDirection is @code{import}; EventName is @code{validPincode}.

Let's assume the provided IController port has an @emph{out} event void
foo().  According to the table in the introduction of this section,
@emph{Provides/out} and @emph{Requires/in} require you to assign foreign
code to a System function.  void foo() will be represented as an Action
object, which we must assign foreign code to.  To assign to an Action
object, we can use a lambda expression:

@example
using System;

namespace MyDznApp @{
  class main @{
    private dzn.Locator dznLoc;
    private dzn.Runtime dznRt;
    private AlarmSystem as;

    public static void Main() @{
      dznLoc = new dzn.Locator();
      dznRt = new dzn.Runtime();

      dznLoc.set(dznRt);
      as = new AlarmSystem(as);
      as.iController.outport.foo = () => @{ /* Foreign implementation of foo() */@};

      as.iController.inport.validPincode();
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example

For more information on lambda expressions in C#, please refer to
@url{https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/programming-guide/statements-expressions-operators/lambda-expressions}.

@node Foreign components in C#
@subsection Foreign components in C#

The interface iLED is provided by the LED component, which is a foreign
component and therefore not generated from your Dezyne models.  The
generated AlarmSystem System component does refer to an object of type
LED, so you will have to make this object yourself.  @strong{Take note
that this object should not be contained in a namespace; the generated
System refers directly to LED.}

A prototype of an LED class that complies to the ILED interface is as
follows:

@example
class LED @{
  public ILED iLed;

  public LED(dzn.Locator locator, String name = "", dzn.Meta parent = null) @{
    iLed = new ILED();

    iLed.inport.setGreen = this.setGreen;
    iLed.inport.setYellow = this.setYellow;
    iLed.inport.setRed = this.setRed;
    iLed.inport.turnOff = this.turnOff;
  @}

  public void setGreen() @{@}
  public void setYellow() @{@}
  public void setRed() @{@}
  public void turnOff() @{@}
@}
@end example

The LED class has a public member named iLed of type ILED; the name of
this member variable has to be the same as the name of the provided
interface of the respective component in your Dezyne model.  Then, in the
constructor the events of ILED that are to be implemented are bound to
the implementations within the LED class.

